07793nam a22010935i 9789814345200DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20122012si     fo  d z      eng d  a2012330067  a97898143452007 a10.1355/97898143452002doi  a(DE-B1597)492263  a(OCoLC)1041998132  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aHV555.I55bF76 2012 4aHV555.I55 7aPOL0110102bisacsh04a320.9598122300aFrom the Ground Up :bPerspectives on Post-Tsunami and Post-Conflict Aceh /ced. by R. Michael Feener, Anthony J. S. Reid, Patrick Daly. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPREFACE -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tThe Contributors -- tGLOSSARY AND ABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION: Unpacking the Challenges of Post-2004 Aceh -- t1 THE SUNDA MEGATHRUST: Past, Present and Future -- tPart I. Reconstruction Efforts -- t2 Disaster Recovery: An International Humanitarian Challenge? -- t3. Linking Relief, Rehabilitation and Development (LRRD) to Social Protection: Lessons from the Early Tsunami Response in Aceh -- t4 CULTURAL HERITAGE AND COMMUNITY RECOVERY IN POST-TSUNAMI ACEH -- t5 Managing POST-DISASTER: Reconstruction Finance International Experience in Public Financial Management -- t6. Between Custom and Law: Protecting the Property Rights of Women after the Tsunami Disaster in Aceh -- t7 Factors Determining the Movements of Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) in Aceh -- t8 Aceh’s Forests as an Asset for Reconstruction? -- tPart II. Conflict Resolution -- t9 Managing Risk. Aceh, the Helsinki Accords and Indonesia’s Democratic Development -- t10 Making Peace Agreements Effective: The Aceh Monitoring Mission Experience -- t11 Justice and the Aceh Peace Process -- t12 Managing Peace in Aceh: The Challenge of Post-Conflict Peace Building -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe tsunami that struck a dozen countries around the Indian Ocean on 26 December 2004 evoked international sympathy on a scale beyond any previous natural disaster. The international relief effort broke all records both in scale and diversity, with seven billion U.S. dollars donated from all over the world through public and private agencies for Sumatra alone. Simply as a reconstruction effort, therefore, the disbursement of those funds and the rebuilding of housing, infrastructure, and economy posed major national and international challenges. However this was not simply a reconstruction effort. Aceh at that time was a war zone, with Indonesia’s military engaged in a major operation to crush a separatist rebellion that had been simmering since 1976. Even though the funds had been donated for tsunami relief, any real reconstruction of Aceh had to consider the impact of the conflict on the well-being of the population, as well as governance and administrative capacities. This volumes serves the purpose not only of discussing some of the lessons of the Aceh reconstruction and peace processes, but also of maintaining critical links between Aceh and the international community after the initial tranches of aid expire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDisaster reliefzIndonesiazAceh. 0aDisaster reliefzIndonesiazNanggroe Aceh Darussalam. 0aDisaster relief--Indonesia--Nanggroe Aceh Darussalam. 0aPeace-buildingzIndonesiazAceh. 0aPeace-buildingzIndonesiazNanggroe Aceh Darussalam. 0aPeace-building--Indonesia--Nanggroe Aceh Darussalam. 0aTsunamiszIndonesiazAceh. 0aTsunamiszIndonesiazNanggroe Aceh Darussalam. 0aTsunamis--Indonesia--Nanggroe Aceh Darussalam. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh1 aAvonius, Lee